nclusion where an economic calculus of one's value crystallizes at the intersections of language and racial difference. By pointing to the nexus of race, capital, and language as the focal point of postwar negotiations of difference and inclusion, Bilingual Brokers probes the faultlines of postwar liberalism in conceptualizing and articulating who is and is not considered to be an American.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexAsian American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aBilingualismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation, Bilingual. 0aMultilingualism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAsian American literature.  aLatino literature.  abilingual personhood.  aflexible inclusion.  alanguage difference.  amulticulturalism.  apostwar liberalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823275335zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823275335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823275335.jpg  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK